-# Wave 13 Codex adversarial review
+# Wave 13 Codex re-review — fix round 1
 
-Reviewed `_meta/plans/wave-13-spec.md`, `_meta/plans/wave-13-summary.md`, and `git diff origin/main..HEAD` excluding `_meta/`, with surrounding implementation and callers.
+Reviewed commit `3867eae1`, the full current implementations and callers, the fix-round summary, and the targeted runnable tests. Bugs 1–3 remain fixed. Bug 5 and the integer-ms accumulation defect are fixed. Bug 4 remains partial because the requested strict BOM-line identity contract was not fully implemented.
 
-## Bug-by-bug result
+## Cross-cutting capacity arithmetic — FIXED
 
-### Bug 1 — FIXED
+`apps/web/app/[locale]/(app)/(modules)/scheduler/_actions/sequence-solver.ts:171-255` now carries `dayUsageMs` through lookup, admission, retry calculation, reservation, and the sequencing run. Reservations add `overlap.overlapMs` directly at `:200`; accumulated bucket state is never converted to hours. The only ms-to-hours conversion is the test-only presentation helper `__dayUsageHoursForTests` at `:372-376`, outside the capacity decision path.
 
-`apps/web/app/[locale]/(app)/(modules)/scheduler/_actions/sequence-solver.ts:341-357` keeps `lastWoByLine` and obtains `previous` with `lastWoByLine.get(lineKey)`. The first WO on any line gets `null`, hence zero changeover. With global order `A1(line A, milk), B1(line B, nuts), B2(line B, soy)`, B1 has no predecessor on line B and no changeover; B2 uses B1 and gets the `nuts -> soy` transition, not global predecessor A1's `milk -> soy`. The added tests pin both the cross-line case and an ordinary same-line pair.
+The capacity configuration still originates as hours and is converted once to milliseconds at `:233-235`. That is a limit conversion, not repeated bucket accumulation; for the tested 6-hour capacity it is the exact integer `21,600,000`. No float-hours bucket state or repeated float accumulation remains on the admission path.
 
-The sequence-selection heuristic at `:330-334` remains global and scores candidate transitions from the global tail, but the actual time-phasing and charged changeover now use the correct per-line predecessor. That residual heuristic behavior does not recreate the reported cross-line charge or discard the real same-line predecessor.
-
-### Bug 2 — FIXED
-
-`sequence-solver.ts:176-265` removed the unchecked return after 400 attempts. A successful placement is returned only after `canReserveCapacity` validates every affected UTC-day overlap and `reserveCapacity` records them; exhaustion throws typed `SequenceCapacityInfeasibleError` (`:24-35`, `:265`). There is no residual unchecked `earliestMs` return when finite capacity applies.
-
-For an 8-hour WO starting at 18:00 UTC on a 6-hour/day line, `[18:00, 02:00)` is accepted as two exact buckets: 6 hours on day 1 and 2 hours on day 2. If no candidate is found in 400 attempts, the exact result is `SequenceCapacityInfeasibleError`, not an unreserved schedule.
-
-### Bug 3 — FIXED
-
-`sequence-solver.ts:183-205` uses the shared half-open `[start,end)` splitter from `planning/schedule/_lib/board.ts:184-194` for both validation and reservation. A 4-hour WO at 23:00 produces exactly 3,600,000 ms on day 1 and 10,800,000 ms on day 2. A WO ending exactly at midnight contributes nothing to the next bucket, while one starting at midnight contributes nothing to the prior bucket, so there is no boundary double-count.
-
-Board read-back uses the same `overlapMsWithUtcDay` semantics at `board.ts:239-247`; its utilization therefore agrees with solver reservation for cross-midnight intervals.
+`sequence-solver.test.ts:593-612` places 360 one-minute reservations, asserts the first UTC-day bucket equals exactly `21,600,000` ms, then proves the 361st starts at `2026-06-25T00:00:00.000Z` and consumes one minute in the next bucket.
 
-### Bug 4 — PARTIAL (`apps/web/app/[locale]/(app)/(modules)/planning/work-orders/_actions/create-work-order-chain.ts:510-513`)
+## Bug 4 — PARTIAL / FAIL
 
-The normal new-chain path correctly threads each BOM line ID through `WipChainEntry` and first matches `WOMaterial.bomItemId`. The duplicate-line test proves two identical WIP products with BOM lines B1/B2 link to their respective material IDs and quantities 300/700.
+Finding:
 
-However, the implementation explicitly retains `fgMaterials.find(row => row.productId === ...)` as a fallback. Concrete failure: two WIP BOM lines reference product P; FG materials contain B1/P and B2/P, but the B2 material has a missing or mismatched `bomItemId` (the stated “legacy” case). The B2 dependency falls back to the first P row, B1, reproducing the original wrong material ID and quantity. The acceptance question asks whether any `find()` by product ID remains; one does. Missing BOM identity must fail explicitly or use a genuinely unique legacy mapping, never silently choose the first repeated product.
+```text
+{severity: high, file: apps/web/app/[locale]/(app)/(modules)/planning/work-orders/_actions/create-work-order-chain.ts:517, claim: The direct find()-by-productId expression was removed, but the behavioral productId fallback remains. When strict bomItemId matching fails, the function filters materials and WIP entries by productId and returns productMatches[0] when each side is unique and the material bomItemId is absent. Therefore a missing bomItemId does not always fail explicitly, contrary to the requested strict identity contract; a single-line chain can still silently link by product. A mismatched non-null bomItemId does reject, and duplicate-product ambiguity rejects. suggested-fix: Delete lines 517-529 and throw a typed missing/mismatched BOM-link error whenever the exact bomItemId lookup at lines 514-515 fails; add a single-product missing-bomItemId negative test as well as retaining the duplicate-product test.}
+```
 
-### Bug 5 — PARTIAL (`apps/web/lib/shared/wall-clock-time.ts:91-98`)
+The requested duplicate-product negative test does exist at `create-work-order-chain.test.ts:467-681`: B1 and B2 use the same product, B2 has `bomItemId: null`, and the result exposes typed `planningError: 'wip_material_link_ambiguous'` without inserting B2's dependency. The production `createWorkOrderChain` lets the thrown `WorkOrderChainError` escape `withOrgContext` before mapping it, so this failure rolls back rather than committing the already inserted B1 dependency. However, that test covers only the ambiguous duplicate case and does not prove the broader stated rule that every missing BOM identity fails.
 
-The ordinary BST/GMT conversions are correct and use `Intl` with the site's IANA timezone: London 09:00 maps to 08:00Z in July and 09:00Z in January. The old capacity-block `...Z` construction is removed, and no other capacity-block caller still appends `Z`. Ambiguous London 01:30 at fall-back selects the standard-time occurrence because candidates are sorted by offset.
+## Bug 5 — FIXED
 
-Nonexistent spring-forward wall times are not handled as documented. `wallClockMatches` compares its formatted time string to the same formatted time string, not to the requested `time`; only the date comparison is meaningful. Concrete scenario: `2026-03-29 01:30 Europe/London` does not exist. Candidate `00:30Z` formats as 00:30 local but is nevertheless accepted because the date matches, so the function returns an instant representing the wrong wall time instead of advancing to the next valid wall minute (02:00 local) or rejecting it. The minute-probe loop at `:128-136` has the same defective predicate. There is also no test for a nonexistent or ambiguous time despite the explicit requirement.
+`apps/web/lib/shared/wall-clock-time.ts:121-136` compares the formatted candidate's hour/minute (and optional second) to parsed requested parts; it no longer compares a formatted string with itself. The exact-candidate helper uses this predicate at `:160-162`, so both the initial candidate set and every minute of the gap probe route through the corrected comparison.
 
-## Cross-cutting review
+For a nonexistent time, `wallClockToInstant` advances requested wall-clock parts minute-by-minute at `:177-183` until a valid local instant exists. The London `2026-03-29 01:30` test proves advancement to local `02:00` / `01:00Z`. For ambiguous times, valid candidates are sorted by UTC offset ascending at `:185`, choosing the standard-time occurrence; the London `2026-10-25 01:30` test proves `01:30Z`, not the BST occurrence `00:30Z`.
 
-### Time arithmetic — BROKEN (`sequence-solver.ts:171-203`)
+## Regression sweep
 
-Bucket state is stored as floating-point hours, then converted back to milliseconds for capacity decisions. This violates the exact-ms requirement and admits over-capacity work after accumulation. Concrete schedule: on a 6-hour bucket, reserve 360 one-minute WOs. Repeated `60000 / 3600000` addition produces `5.999999999999984` hours, which reads back as `21,599,999.999999944` ms. The solver therefore sees `60,000.000000056` ms remaining and accepts a 361st one-minute WO, exceeding capacity by one minute. Store integer milliseconds in the map and convert to hours only for presentation/tests.
+- Bug 1 remains fixed: actual predecessor and charged changeover are still tracked per production line via `lastWoByLine`.
+- Bug 2 remains fixed: finite-capacity placement still throws `SequenceCapacityInfeasibleError` after bounded exhaustion; there is no unchecked placement return.
+- Bug 3 remains fixed: validation and reservation still share half-open UTC-day overlap splitting, including exact-midnight boundaries.
+- No float-hours accumulation remains in scheduler capacity bucket state. Board utilization converts exact overlaps to hours only for display/read-back aggregation, not solver admission.
+- No `... + 'Z'`, template-literal `Z` append, or equivalent UTC-forcing construction remains in the capacity-block wall-clock conversion path. The unrelated schedule UI's explicit UTC day-label construction is not a capacity-block parser.
+- No SQL reserved-keyword alias was introduced by the fix round.
 
-### Complexity / SQL
+## Verification evidence
 
-The new capacity work is O(number of affected day buckets) per placement attempt, capped at 400 attempts; the existing global sequencing remains O(n²). This is reasonable for normal-duration WOs, although extremely long intervals multiply the per-attempt day scan. No new SQL uses a reserved-keyword alias. The added site-timezone query is org- and site-scoped.
